</strong><strong>By:</strong><strong></strong>Robert McMillan<br>
  <strong>IDG News Service April 9, 2005 --</strong> The U.S. should look to regions like China and the E.U. for ways to improve intellectual property (IP) policy, or it runs the risk of driving business out of the country, an IBM (Profile, Products, Articles) executive said Wednesday during a keynote address at the Open Source Business Conference in San Francisco. Describing the U.S. patent policy as &quot;lousy,&quot; IBM Vice President of Technology and Strategy Irving Wladawsky-Berger said that the U.S. Patent Office has been simply too lax in granting patents. &quot;Any idiot can get a patent for something that should never be granted a patent,&quot; he said. .. .<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/05/04/07/HNpatentpolicy_1.html">Full Story </a></p>
