</strong><strong>By:</strong><strong></strong>Declan McCullagh<br>
  <strong>CNET News.com, April 26, 2005 --</strong> The head of the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office has endorsed some key reforms that Congress is scheduled to consider this year. Patent Office chief Jon Dudas said Monday that federal law should be changed to award a patent to the first person to file a claim and to permit review of a patent after it is granted. Currently patents are awarded to the first person who concocted the invention, a timeframe that can be difficult to prove. The Patent Office already has a backlog of 490,000 applications and is planning to hire 800 more patent examiners, bringing its total to 4,400. It approves more than 500 patents per day. Monday's hearing before a Senate Judiciary subcommittee kicked off a process that's expected to end in new legislation being drafted by the end of the year. &hellip; <a href="http://news.com.com/2100-1028_3-5683954.html">Full Story
