        <p class="style82"> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em> <strong><em>        <strong><em> What price ideological purity?</em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong></em></strong><em><em><em><em><em><em><em><em><em> What do you do when ideological purity is, well, an article of faith, but you&rsquo;ve got a global open source project to manage? The result, unfortunately, is that when you&rsquo;re also Linus Torvalds, the keeper of the Linux flame, you may have to violate a fundamental principle laid down by another icon: R. Crumb&rsquo;s venerable Mr. Natural, who first laid down the following edict some thirty years ago: &ldquo;Always use the right tool for the job.&rdquo; That still leaves the definition of &ldquo;right&rdquo; open, of course, and in Linux, &ldquo;right&rdquo; means &ldquo;open&rdquo;, whether there&rsquo;s an adequate technical alternative available or not. </em></em></em></em></em></em></em></em></em> </p></td>
